{
  "doc_id": "29143",
  "text": "In contrast to HBV, HCV reaches high serum titres within one week of infection [CITATION_1] . Adaptive cellular immune responses are delayed by at least one month, and humoral immune responses by at least two months, raising the hypothesis that the virus 'outpaces' the adaptive immune response [CITATION_2] . Accordingly, clinical symptoms, which are attributed to T-cell-mediated liver injury and are common in acute hepatitis B, are rarely observed in infection with HCV. Approximately 8-12 weeks after infection HCV-specific antibodies might become detectable around this time, later, or not at all, and they do not indicate the outcome of infection [CITATION_3] .",
